-- Italian Stocks Advance; Bulgari, Exor, Mediaset, Saipem, and Tenaris Move
-- Francesca Cinelli
-- 2010-06-21T15:50:40Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-21/enel-intesa-sanpaolo-telecom-italia-unicredit-italian-equity-preview.html

          
          
             Italy’s  FTSE MIB Index  rose for a
third sesssion, gaining 58.13, or 0.3 percent, to 20,810.44 in
Milan.  
 The following stocks were among the most active on the
Italian market today.  
 A2A SpA  (A2A IM) ended an eight-session gain, falling 2.7
cents, or 2.2 percent, to 1.22 euros. Shares of Italy’s biggest
municipal utility traded without the right to a dividend of 7
cents apiece.  
 Ansaldo STS SpA  (STS IM) advanced 21 cents, or 1.6 percent,
to 13.17 euros after Finmeccanica SpA’s railway-technology unit
won a 43.7 million-euro ($54.4 million) contract in Genoa.  
 Banca Monte dei Paschi di Siena SpA  (BMPS IM) retreated 0.8
percent to 99.85. Citigroup Inc. trimmed its price estimates on
Italian banks, saying in a note that “the real issue is low
profitability.” The brokerage said that “profitability is
expected to increase significantly, but should remain below the
cost of equity for all banks excluding  Intesa Sanpaolo SpA  (ISP
IM).” Intesa is Citigroup’s preferred stock among Italian
banks.  Banca Popolare di Milano Scrl  (PMI IM) lost 1.7 percent
to 3.72 euros.  Banco Popolare SC  (BP IM) declined 1.3 percent to
4.76 euros. Intesa shares fell 0.3 percent to 2.39 euros.  
 Bulgari SpA  (BUL IM), the world’s third-largest jeweler,
advanced for a third session, gaining 22 cents, or 3.5 percent,
to 6.55 euros. Luxury stocks rose across Europe on optimism that
China’s relaxation of the yuan’s dollar peg will boost the value
of luxury sales from that market.  
 Buzzi Unicem SpA  (BZU IM), Italy’s second-biggest cement
maker, rose 15 cents, or 1.7 percent, to 9.09 euros as
construction shares were among the best performers in Europe
today.  Italcementi SpA  (IT IM), Italy’s biggest cement maker,
increased 17.5 cents, or 2.5 percent, to 7.11 euros.  
 Exor SpA  (EXO IM), Fiat SpA’s main shareholder, increased
28 cents, or 2 percent, to 14.43 euros, the highest in eight
months. Mediobanca Securities upgraded the stock to
“outperform” from “neutral,” saying in a note that “there
is room for a reshuffle in the portfolio which will lead to a
discount reduction.”  
 Fiat SpA  (F IM) advanced 16.5 cents, or 1.8 percent, to
9.62 euros, a third straight gain. Italy’s largest manufacturer
may create a new company for its Pomigliano d’Arco factory near
Naples, la Repubblica reported, without saying where it got the
information.  
 Gemina SpA  (GEM IM) climbed 1.05 cents, or 1.9 percent, to
56.5 cents. Citigroup upgraded the owner of Rome’s airports
operator to “buy” from “hold.” The brokerage said that “the
recovery has started,” citing traffic performance.  
 Gruppo Editoriale L’Espresso SpA  (ES IM) surged 11.1 cents,
or 6.2 percent, to 1.89 euros, the highest in almost five weeks.
Citigroup upgraded the publisher to “hold” from “sell.”  
 Mediaset SpA  (MS IM) increased 13.75 cents, or 2.8 percent,
to 5.09 euros, erasing losses on June 18. Italy’s biggest
private television broadcaster was upgraded to “buy” from
“hold” at Citigroup.  
 Prysmian SpA  (PRY IM) rose 25 cents, or 1.9 percent, to
13.45 euros, a second session of gains. Exane BNP Paribas lifted
its price estimate on the world’s second-biggest cable maker by
5 percent to 14.7 euros.  
 Saipem SpA  (SPM IM), Europe’s largest oilfield-services
provider, surged 61 cents, or 2.3 percent, to 27.52 euros. Crude
rose to the highest in six weeks on increased confidence in the
global economic recovery after China, the world’s second-largest
energy consumer, signaled an end to the yuan’s fixed rate to the
dollar.  Tenaris SA  (TEN IM), the world’s biggest maker of
seamless steel tubes for oil and gas extraction, increased 49.99
cents, or 3.2 percent, to 15.71 euros.  
 Unipol Gruppo Finanziario SpA  (UNI IM) declined 0.73 cents,
or 1.2 percent, to 62.4 cents. The capital increase of Italy’s
third-largest insurer started today. Unipol had its price
estimate trimmed at JPMorgan Cazenove, Credit Suisse Group AG,
and Cheuvreux.  
